Text: EDIT: It seems like Trinity series processors have it's own BAPM switch in source. It's located in
Label: O

Text: drivers/gpu/drm/radeon/trinity_dpm.c
Label: Path / Url

Text: and it's (at the time of writing) enabled only for MSI boards, because of stability issues. To enable it, open this file, find this line:
Label: O

Text: pi->enable_bapm = false;
Label: File Content (Not Code)

Text: Change false to true, then compile and install new kernel. You should get a kernel panic boost working now. Keep in mind that CPU power is also shared with GPU, so you'll almost never get the highest frequency available if GPU is also in use.
Label: O

Text:
I have followed this to fix the issue and did the following :


Ensured permissions are not too open by OpenSSH standards.
Label: O

Text:
chmod go-w ~/
chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
Label: Command / Code

Text: Created a authorized_keys file in host computer by
Label: O

Text: ssh-copy-id host@127.0.0.1
Label: Command / Code

Text:
and copied the authorized_keys file to the server, changed ownership and permissions as required then.


Still the issue persists. I was able to ssh into the server successfully using password before trying to use Publickey authentication. Has anyone else faced similar issues?

Edit :

There was a new line added to the output when I tried to ssh in later : Agent admitted failure to sign using the key.. Some googling led to this issue. The issue is called gnome-keyring interference. When I tried SSH_AUTH_SOCK=0 ssh user@domain I was able to login into the server successfully using publickey authentication. Thank you all for your contribution.
Label: O

Text:
On Monday I've upgraded to from Ubuntu 11.04 (my initial installation) to 11.10 and now I can't build gcc from source anymore. Since I forgot to uninstall the gcc package before the upgrade, Ubuntu replaced my 4.7.0 compiler with it's stable 4.6.1. So I tried to build the SVN sources again, but it fails. I've most recently tried it with SVN revision 180193.

After some time, the build fails with the following message:
Label: O
Error Message / Stack Trace

Text: I've cofigured it with:
Label: O

Text: ~/devel/gcc/build$ ../src/configure --prefix=/usr --enable-languages=c++
Label: Command / Code

Text: And make it with:
Label: O

Text: ~/devel/gcc/build$ make -j4
Label: Command / Code

Text: Just to be sure, I did a
Label: O

Text: rm -rf *
Label: Command / Code

Text:
in the build directory in case there's some broken stuff inside. Didn't help, though.



That's the backstory. I tried to fix it and searched for the bits/predefs.h. It's inside
Label: O

Text: /usr/include/i386-linux-gnu
Label: Path / Url

Text: . I temporarily fixed the problem by doing
Label: O

Text: ~/devel/gcc/build$ C_INCLUDE_PATH=/usr/include/i386-linux-gnu make -j4
Label: Command / Code

Text:
Which is only temporary because now gcc complains that it can't find crti.o.

Which i can find in
Label: O

Text: /usr/lib/i386-linux-gnu
Label: Path / Url

Text:
. Now i could also set C_LIBRARY_PATH - actually it doesn't work - but I feel like I'm fighting the system here. Also, even if it succeeds, my newly built compiler would also not know about the i386-linux-gnu stuff. So I would have to set C_LIBRARY_PATH and C_INCLUDE_PATH before every build of every project I have. I could add it to my .bashrc but that subverts the system even more.

So, how do I tell the build process:


That there are additional include/lib directories, and
That it should build a gcc which respects them too?




Edit: I forgot to include the command which causes the above error message. Also I can think of another solution: Copy the stuff from
Label: O

Text: /usr/include/i386-linux-gnu to /usr/include
Label: Path / Url

Text: (same thing for
Label: O

Text: /usr/lib/i386-linux-gnu to /usr/lib
Label: Path / Url

Text: ). But that doesn't feel right, either. Finally, the system's gcc 4.6.1 can compile other applications just fine, except mine, which use C++11 features not present in the 4.6 series.

Label: O

Text:
# See /usr/share/postfix/main.cf.dist for a commented, more complete version


# Debian specific:  Specifying a file name will cause the first
# line of that file to be used as the name.  The Debian default
# is /etc/mailname.
#myorigin = /etc/mailname

smtpd_banner = $myhostname ESMTP $mail_name (Debian/GNU)

# appending .domain is the MUA's job.

# TLS parameters

Installed msmtp and set it up to work with an external gmail account successfully. 
Uncommented and configured
Label: O

Text: /etc/zfs/zed.d/zed.rc
Label: Path / Url

Text: Set ZED_NOTIFY_VERBOSE=1
Label: Command / Code

Text:
Ran zpool scrub expecting to receive a notification of the clean scrub, no email is sent


This is the only post that I can find relating to ZFS/ZED configuration, however I was unable to get it to work:
Label: O

Text: http://louwrentius.com/the-zfs-event-daemon-on-linux.html
Label: Path / Url

Text:
Update:
Both responses from Mumblepins and Martin led to the fix. Below are the full steps needed to get this to work:


Install msmtp and set it up to work with an external email account (gmail or whatever)
Install s-nail and msmtp-mta packages to map msmtp to the mail command
Uncomment and configure
Label: O

Text: /etc/zfs/zed.d/zed.rc
Label: Path / Url

Text:
(keeping ZED_EMAIL_PROG="mail")
systemctl enable zed
